   <body>
      <context>
         <p>Follow this procedure to inspect for leaks on the MFC after replacement:</p>
      </context>
      <ol>
         <li>
            <p>Inspect the MFC for any possible leaks after the burner is restarted.</p>
            <p>
               <ul>
                  <li>Use soapy water.</li>
               </ul>
            </p>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>If a leak has occurred at the flange</p>
            <p>
               <ul>
                  <li>Tighten the flange bolts.</li>
               </ul>
            </p>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Tools Required Adjustable wrench, flange gaskets. </p>
            <p>If the leak continues:<ul>
                  <li>Switch back to the spare gas and oxygen circuit.</li>
                  <li>Lockout tagout the leaking gas and oxygen circuit, and replace the flange
                     gasket.</li>
               </ul>
            </p>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>After the burner is lit:</p>
            <p>
               <ul>
                  <li>Go the display and press the <uicontrol>Logo</uicontrol> button to activate
                     the backlight.</li>
                  <li>Verify that the flow is within 5% of the setpoint. </li>
               </ul>
               <p>
                  <fig id="fig_zjk_h5m_vcc">
                     <image href="media/image1.jpg"
                            placement="break"
                            id="image_akk_h5m_vcc"
                            align="center"/>
                  </fig>
               </p>
            </p>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Verify that the flow rates displayed on each MFC are at the setpoint valules on the DFC.</p>
            <p>
               <p>
                  <fig id="fig_bfr_35m_vcc">
                     <image href="media/image2.jpg"
                            placement="break"
                            id="image_cfr_35m_vcc"
                            align="center"/>
                  </fig>
               </p>
            </p>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>If there is a deviation between the actual flow and the setpoint flow:</p>
            <p>
               <ul>
                  <li>There may be a possible line clog.</li>
                  <li>The MFC may require maintenance or repair.</li>
               </ul>
            </p>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>In DFC, go to the Melter H3C screen and click the <uicontrol>Comb. Skid
                  1</uicontrol>, <uicontrol>Comb. Skid 2</uicontrol>, or <uicontrol>Comb. Skid
                  3</uicontrol> tabs.</p>
            <p>
               <ul>
                  <li>Verify that the line pressures are at similar values. </li>
               </ul>
               <p>
                  <fig id="fig_wvl_p5m_vcc">
                     <image href="media/image3.jpg"
                            placement="break"
                            id="image_xvl_p5m_vcc"
                            align="center"/>
                  </fig>
               </p>
            </p>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>If a line pressure is more than 0.35 bar (5.08 psi) higher than the other
               values:</p>
            <p>
               <ul>
                  <li>Inspect for any possible clogged lines between the MFC and burner.</li>
               </ul>
            </p>
         </li>
      </ol>
